<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1325,455,1201]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Diagnosis.­ Similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wheeler and Forrest" authorityYear="2002" box="[537,778,455,480]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Elachiptera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cultrata">
<emphasis box="[537,778,455,480]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Elachiptera cultrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except as follows: Arista broad and parallelsided for almost entire length, narrowing only at tip (
<figureCitation box="[880,966,495,521]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 ­ 15" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1760,1784]" captionTargetBox="[330,1233,674,1711]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[319,1248,674,1729]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11 ­ 15. Elachiptera eulophus. 11. hind tibia, and basal tarsal segments (lateral); 12. scutellum; 13. antenna; 14. male genitalia (posterior); 15. male genitalia (lateral). Scale bar = 0.1 mm (Figs. 14 ­ 15)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155635/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[934,966,495,521]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
); hind tibia with strong, black, preapical ventral spur, as long as or longer than tibial diameter (
<figureCitation box="[1025,1112,535,561]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 ­ 15" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1760,1784]" captionTargetBox="[330,1233,674,1711]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[319,1248,674,1729]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11 ­ 15. Elachiptera eulophus. 11. hind tibia, and basal tarsal segments (lateral); 12. scutellum; 13. antenna; 14. male genitalia (posterior); 15. male genitalia (lateral). Scale bar = 0.1 mm (Figs. 14 ­ 15)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155635/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[1081,1112,535,561]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
); abdominal tergites mostly light brown, often darker medially. Male postabdomen (
<figureCitation box="[1083,1224,575,601]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 ­ 15" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1760,1784]" captionTargetBox="[330,1233,674,1711]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[319,1248,674,1729]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11 ­ 15. Elachiptera eulophus. 11. hind tibia, and basal tarsal segments (lateral); 12. scutellum; 13. antenna; 14. male genitalia (posterior); 15. male genitalia (lateral). Scale bar = 0.1 mm (Figs. 14 ­ 15)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155635/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Figs. 
<number box="[1152,1224,575,601]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="14.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="14.0">14­15</number>
</figureCitation>
): cercus triangular, projecting ventrally, not posteriorly, with single long seta and a few shorter setae; cerci widely separated by broadly rounded cleft (
<figureCitation box="[920,1007,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 ­ 15" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1760,1784]" captionTargetBox="[330,1233,674,1711]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[319,1248,674,1729]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11 ­ 15. Elachiptera eulophus. 11. hind tibia, and basal tarsal segments (lateral); 12. scutellum; 13. antenna; 14. male genitalia (posterior); 15. male genitalia (lateral). Scale bar = 0.1 mm (Figs. 14 ­ 15)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155635/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[975,1007,655,681]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
); distiphallus weakly sclerotized, with slightly expanded, blunt apex (
<figureCitation box="[781,868,695,721]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 ­ 15" captionStartId="7.[264,382,1760,1784]" captionTargetBox="[330,1233,674,1711]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[319,1248,674,1729]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11 ­ 15. Elachiptera eulophus. 11. hind tibia, and basal tarsal segments (lateral); 12. scutellum; 13. antenna; 14. male genitalia (posterior); 15. male genitalia (lateral). Scale bar = 0.1 mm (Figs. 14 ­ 15)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155635/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[836,868,695,721]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
